A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 State Government – State House Trust – Ten Commandments Monument
3 Display Act
4 FOR the purpose of requiring a certain Ten Commandments Monument to be placed on the
5 grounds of the Maryland State House; requiring the Commission on Artistic Property
6 to oversee the care and maintenance of the monument; establishing the Commission
7 on the Ten Commandments Monument; and generally relating to a Ten
8 Commandments Monument.
9 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
10 Article – State Government
11 Section 9–1016 and 9–1021
12 Annotated Code of Maryland
13 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2024 Supplement)
14 Preamble
15 WHEREAS, The Ten Commandments, found in the Bible at Exodus 20:1–17 and
16 Deuteronomy 5:6–21, are an important component of the moral foundation of the laws and
17 legal system of the United States of America and of the State of Maryland; and
18 WHEREAS, The courts of the United States and various states frequently cite the
19 Ten Commandments in published decisions; and
20 WHEREAS, In 2005, the U.S. Supreme Court recognized that it is permissible to
21 display the Ten Commandments on government property in Van Orden v. Perry; and
22 WHEREAS, In 2019, the U.S. Supreme Court further recognized that the Ten
23 Commandments “have historical significance as one of the foundations of our legal system”,
24 in American Legion v. American Humanists Association, and the court also ruled that the
